flowRoot.flowPara: The ranking algorithm used by this console is called TrueSkill. It was developed by Microsoft as the ranking system used for Xbox Live. It's most important feature compared to other ranking systems, such as elo, is that it can deal with team-vs-team matches even in the face of changing team compositions. Fun fact: this algorithm can also deal with more than two two teams, with teams of more than two players, with matches between unequally sized teams, and even with players joining teams halfway through the match. However, none of these features are implemented here.

The fundamental way in which a player's skill is stored is using two numbers, mu and sigma, which describe a bell-curve that represents the system's confidence in the player's true skill (hence the name). Bayesian statistics are used to update the skills after every match result. Winning a match always results in an increase in mu (and, vice versa, losing always results in a decrease in mu). Unlikely match results affect mu more strongly but may decrease sigma. A match only affects the skill levels of the players involved.

To compare players we calculate their 'level'. The level of a player is defined as mu-3*sigma. I.e. the skill level that the system is ~99% sure that the player is above. For new players mu equals 25 and sigma equals 25/3 and therefore the initial level is 0. Several players can have the same level.

The rank of a player is defined as the position on the leader board when sorting by (rounded) level. When multiple players are at the same level they share the positions which is displayed as a hyphened range. Mu and sigma are always displayed using a separating slash.

This machine used to be a self-order photo kiosk. It was rescued from a dumpster by a friend of mine who donated it to Hackerspace Nijmegen. It has been collecting more dust there in a corner until I realised that it could become this score-keeping terminal. I hope it brings you fun in it's second life.

The style of this interface is inspired by the iconic LCARS User Interface. LCARS was conceived and designed by Michael Okuda and Gene Roddenberry for Start Trek: The Next Generation in 1987. The interface, which was at first produced on plexiglass sheets with printed designs on them, was originally a way to save costs compared to panels of physical buttons and switches.

This console was designed and executed by Sjoerd Timmer. I make software for astrophysics at the Radboud Radio Lab. In my evenings and weekends I like to tinker with electronics, old hardware, 3d printers, etc. If you have any feedback on this installation feel free to contact me at s.timmer@astro.ru.nl.
